choices.text: For a permutation P[1... N] of integers from 1 to N, function f is defined as follows: $f(i, j) = \left\{\begin{array}{ll}{P [ i ]} & {\text{if} j = 1} \\{f(P [ i ], j - 1)} & {\text{otherwise}} \end{array} \right.$ Let g(i) be the minimum positive integer j such that f(i, j) = i. We can show such j always exists. For given N, A, B, find a permutation P of integers from 1 to N such that for 1   i   N, g(i) equals either A or B.
